Enforces "soft-tier rationale comment" conventions on Rust source as a CI/pre-commit gate — a Python MVP standing in for a future dylint rule (see docs/DYLINT_RULES.md). Run as a script; exits 1 with failure messages on stderr if any file violates the rules, 0 otherwise.

Thresholds are module-level constants: functions ≥30 lines (`SOFT_FN_LINES`) need a `// rationale: <text>` comment on the line immediately preceding `fn` (blank lines/attributes in between are tolerated) or they fail; functions ≥80 lines (`HARD_FN_LINES`) fail unconditionally regardless of rationale. Files ≥250 lines (`SOFT_FILE_LINES`) need a leading `// rationale:` comment (after any `//!` inner doc block) or fail; files ≥400 lines (`HARD_FILE_LINES`) fail unconditionally. Changing any of these four constants changes CI behavior directly — no other file mirrors them today, but a future dylint rule is expected to reimplement the same tiers per the module docstring.

Function boundaries are found by a brace-balance heuristic (`find_fn_end`), not a real parser: it starts counting braces from the line matching `FN_RE` and tracks depth until it returns to zero. `FN_RE` matches `fn` preceded by optional `pub(...)`, `async`/`const`/`unsafe`/`extern "..."` modifiers, but only for a name starting with `[A-Za-z_]`. Bodyless declarations (trait method signatures, `extern` fn decls) are detected separately by `is_bodyless_fn_decl`, which scans up to 12 lines ahead for a `;` before any `{` — without this check the brace-balance scan would run unbounded into unrelated following code and report a bogus function length. `strip_strings_and_comments` does a single-pass strip of string literals and `//` comments before brace counting; it does **not** handle multi-line strings or `/* */` block comments, an acknowledged gap for this MVP.

`tracked_rs_files(root)` enumerates `.rs` files via `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard -- '*.rs'`, deliberately not a filesystem walk — `rglob` would descend into `target/` before any skip logic and can race a concurrent cargo/rust-analyzer build, producing nondeterministic failures. Git enumeration also naturally excludes ignored paths. If git invocation fails (`OSError`/`CalledProcessError`), the script prints a `FAIL:` line and calls `sys.exit(1)` immediately rather than propagating an exception.

Key functions: `check_file(path: Path) -> list[str]` returns all failure messages for one file (empty = pass), covering both the file-length and per-function checks. `has_rationale_before(lines, fn_idx) -> bool` and `file_has_rationale_at_top(lines) -> bool` implement the two rationale-comment lookups respectively. `main()` accepts an optional root path as `sys.argv[1]` (defaults to cwd); if that path is itself a file, it's checked directly instead of triggering the git-based repo scan — useful for editor-integration/single-file invocation.